{
	"nodes":[
		{"id":"overview","type":"text","text":"Obsidian Task Stream Architecture\n\nThis canvas explains the concrete runtime path for task status updates inside the Obsidian plugin.\n\nWhat this map answers:\n1. Who owns canonical task state?\n2. How does the plugin receive updates?\n3. Why can status or result-node sync get stuck?\n4. What do active-task streams and running-task streams each do?\n\nShort answer:\n- the daemon owns truth\n- the plugin consumes daemon task updates over SSE\n- mergeTask() is the central fan-in point inside the plugin\n- canvas result-node sync happens only after a merged task reaches the right completed state","x":-1880,"y":-640,"width":620,"height":420,"color":"2"},
		{"id":"source-of-truth","type":"text","text":"Layer 1: Canonical task state lives in the daemon\n\nOwner:\n- apps/openagent-daemon/src/server.js\n\nPersisted in:\n- ~/.openagent/daemon-state.json\n\nThe daemon is authoritative for:\n- taskId\n- threadId\n- currentTurnId\n- status\n- messages\n- runtimeConfig\n- canvasBinding\n\nImportant implication:\nThe plugin is not the source of truth.\nIf the plugin UI falls behind, the daemon task record is still the canonical answer.","x":-1100,"y":-860,"width":500,"height":360,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"daemon-events","type":"text","text":"Layer 2: Runtime notifications become task.updated events\n\nCodex runtime notifications include things like:\n- turn/started\n- item/agentMessage/delta\n- item/toolCall/outputDelta\n- turn/completed\n\nThe daemon handles those notifications, patches the matching task, then publishes a task.updated SSE event.\n\nThis is the handoff from runtime state to plugin-visible state.","x":-1100,"y":-420,"width":500,"height":300,"color":"3"},
		{"id":"sse-route","type":"text","text":"Layer 3: SSE route exposed by the daemon\n\nRoute:\nGET /tasks/:taskId/stream\n\nBehavior:\n- verifies the task exists\n- writes an initial ready event\n- keeps the HTTP connection open\n- pushes event: task.updated frames as task state changes\n\nThis is the only realtime channel the plugin uses for task updates.\n\nWithout poll, if nothing is subscribed to this route, the plugin will not see live task changes.","x":-1100,"y":-40,"width":500,"height":320,"color":"6"},
		{"id":"plugin-client","type":"text","text":"Layer 4: OpenAgentApiClient parses SSE frames\n\nOwner:\n- openTaskStream(taskId, handlers)\n\nResponsibilities:\n- open HTTP request to /tasks/:taskId/stream\n- parse event/data blocks from the response body\n- call onEvent(payload)\n- detect close/end/error paths\n- surface stream failures\n\nThis layer is just transport. It does not decide what task should be active or when result nodes are written.","x":-420,"y":-420,"width":500,"height":320,"color":"5"},
		{"id":"active-task-stream","type":"text","text":"Layer 5A: Active-task stream\n\nWhat it watches:\n- uiState.activeTaskId only\n\nWhy it exists:\n- keep the currently opened conversation live\n- update status and chat content in realtime\n- drive result-node sync quickly for the task the user is focused on\n\nImportant behavior:\n- when activeTaskId changes, the old active stream is disposed\n- the new active task gets a new stream session\n- if that stream drops, the plugin now refreshes once and reconnects","x":260,"y":-640,"width":520,"height":360,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"running-task-streams","type":"text","text":"Layer 5B: Running-task background streams\n\nWhat they watch:\n- every task that is still starting/running\n- except the one already covered by the active-task stream\n\nWhy they exist:\n- a running task can outlive the current active selection\n- the panel can clear active conversation on deselect\n- but the task still needs to be observed until it reaches idle/error\n- otherwise final status and result-node sync can be missed\n\nThis is the replacement for old running-task polling.\n\nDesign goal:\nNo interval poll, but still no lost completion state.","x":260,"y":-180,"width":520,"height":380,"color":"3"},
		{"id":"merge-task","type":"text","text":"Layer 6: mergeTask() is the central plugin fan-in\n\nWhenever a task arrives from:\n- refreshTasks()\n- refreshTask(taskId)\n- active-task stream event\n- running-task stream event\n- updateTaskCanvasBinding() response\n\nit flows through mergeTask().\n\nmergeTask() then:\n1. normalizes task data for local store\n2. writes into tasksById\n3. syncs active-task selection against canvas context\n4. schedules node highlight sync\n5. may trigger result-node sync\n6. reconciles running-task stream subscriptions","x":920,"y":-420,"width":560,"height":360,"color":"2"},
		{"id":"selection-sync","type":"text","text":"Cross-cutting behavior: selection sync can change activeTaskId\n\nThe selection snapshot poll still exists for canvas selection only.\n\nThat logic can:\n- pick a task from current node selection\n- keep the current task if it still matches canvas context\n- clear activeTaskId on explicit deselection\n\nImportant nuance:\nUI ownership and runtime ownership are different.\nThe UI is allowed to clear active conversation, but the task may still be running in the daemon.\n\nThat is why running-task background streams now matter.","x":920,"y":40,"width":560,"height":340,"color":"1"},
		{"id":"result-sync","type":"text","text":"Layer 7: Result node sync\n\nResult-node sync does not happen just because an SSE frame arrived.\n\nIt happens only when the merged task has the right shape:\n- valid canvas source node\n- assistant message text available\n- current message belongs to the current active source context\n- task status is idle\n- no active turn is still running\n\nIf the plugin never sees that final completed task state, result sync can be skipped.\nThat is the exact failure mode we were chasing.","x":1600,"y":-420,"width":520,"height":340,"color":"6"},
		{"id":"drop-recovery","type":"text","text":"Failure handling: stream drop recovery\n\nCurrent recovery path for both active-task and running-task streams:\n1. detect stream end/close/error\n2. call refreshTask(taskId) once\n3. merge the canonical daemon task back into plugin state\n4. if the task is still eligible, reconnect after 1.5s\n\nThis covers the case where:\n- runtime finished in the daemon\n- but the plugin lost the live stream before seeing the last idle update","x":1600,"y":20,"width":520,"height":300,"color":"5"},
		{"id":"why-status-drops","type":"text","text":"Why task status can still look like it 'drops'\n\nThere are two different problems that can feel similar:\n\nA. Transport problem\n- SSE stream closes or stalls\n- plugin misses the latest update\n\nB. Ownership problem\n- activeTaskId changes because selection/UI context changed\n- the conversation disappears from the panel\n- but the daemon task is still progressing\n\nThe new running-task streams are specifically there to prevent B from hiding the task's real final state.","x":1600,"y":380,"width":520,"height":320,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"what-is-not-polled","type":"text","text":"What is no longer polled\n\nRemoved:\n- running task poll every 1.5s\n\nStill present:\n- selection snapshot poll every 250ms\n- daemon health poll every 10s\n- dev smoke poll when enabled\n\nImportant boundary:\nTask status propagation is now stream-driven, not interval-driven.","x":260,"y":280,"width":520,"height":220,"color":"2"},
		{"id":"mental-model","type":"text","text":"Mental model to keep in your head\n\n1. daemon owns truth\n2. daemon publishes task.updated over SSE\n3. plugin consumes SSE through task streams\n4. every incoming task goes through mergeTask()\n5. mergeTask() is where UI state and canvas sync fan out\n6. completion must be observed inside the plugin for result-node sync to happen\n\nIf this mental model feels shaky anywhere, that is where the architecture is currently soft.","x":920,"y":460,"width":560,"height":320,"color":"6"},
		{"id":"plugin-main-file","type":"file","file":"apps/obsidian-plugin/main.js","x":-420,"y":-860,"width":420,"height":240},
		{"id":"daemon-server-file","type":"file","file":"apps/openagent-daemon/src/server.js","x":-420,"y":-40,"width":420,"height":240},
		{"id":"architecture-doc-file","type":"file","file":"docs/ARCHITECTURE.md","x":920,"y":-860,"width":420,"height":220},
		{"id":"stream-flow-doc-file","type":"file","file":"docs/OBSIDIAN_TASK_STREAM_FLOW.md","x":1600,"y":-860,"width":420,"height":220}
	],
